The Five-City Weave

Five cities form a full-chain legitimacy corridor for goods, people, and
legal authority. Remove any one and the others accumulate strain in specific,
predictable ways. The network is not an alliance. It is a co-dependency that
none fully chose and none can easily exit.

  Midgaard - the inland legitimacy engine. Registries, charters,
  sealed-warrant governance, codified arbitration. The city that other cities
  must reckon with regardless of whether they want to.

  Kiess - the legal-memory city built on Evermeet's ruins along Roc Road.
  Anti-secrecy charter doctrine, three-power governance, and the most
  formally principled anti-Conclave record in the network.

  Kowloon - the northern throughput and labor-delta coordination node.
  The city that moves things and counts them. Its Neon Covenant governance
  is the most institutionally stable of the five.

  Saltglass and Rakuen - the southern hazard screening municipality and
  route-resilience broker. Three times petitioned for annexation into
  Midgaard. Three times refused.

  Mafdet - the maritime legalization authority at the Saltglass Reach's
  terminus, where the inland world meets the sea. Its dual-attestation
  protocol converts inland witness-marked cargo into shipborne contract
  cargo.

Together they form the chain: origin claim, then overland custody,
then dispute adjudication, then hazard screening, then ocean
transfer.

Midgaard and Kowloon share the deepest tension: both participated in the
Conclave's condemned-debtor transfer apparatus. Both cities' Reckoning
factions seek exposure. Both Continuity factions seek burial. The shared
institutional guilt creates perverse solidarity.

Kiess and Midgaard cooperate on road-warden intelligence along the Roc Road
but clash over sealed-warrant governance. Kiess's founding charter was written
specifically to repudiate what Midgaard's Continuity faction insists was
acceptable wartime triage.

Rakuen's repeated annexation requests transformed all five-city relations.
Founded to reject Midgaard procedural dominance, it became the city most
insistent on joining that system. The contradiction now drives intercity law.
